      "writtenOn": "2020-03-19T07:57:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "in https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/infra/luci/luci-go/+/2107340/2/milo/frontend/resultui/src/models/test_node.ts#152 you said that there is a benefit of checking nextSeg !\u003d\u003d undefined. I did not understand that. \nnextSeg can be undefined iff test.idSegs is empty. In particular, a valid segment is always a string.\nso I still think the code would be cleaner if we did\n\n  if (test.idSegs.length \u003d\u003d 0) {\n    this.tests.push(test.test);\n    return;\n  }\n\n  const nextSeg \u003d test.idSegs.pop();",
